WEBVTT

00:02.135 --> 00:03.268
(monitors beeping,
air hoses hissing)
okay, people. Mmm.

00:03.270 --> 00:05.137
Tavi is a minimally
invasive way

00:05.139 --> 00:07.272
Of replacing a diseased
aortic valve.

00:07.274 --> 00:09.274
In the old days,
we would crack the chest,

00:09.276 --> 00:10.476
Do open heart surgery.

00:10.478 --> 00:12.144
But this takes way less time,

00:12.146 --> 00:15.114
And for some high-risk patients,
it's the only option.

00:15.116 --> 00:18.684
So today we are going to
replace our diseased pig's valve

00:18.686 --> 00:21.020
With one made of
bovine tissue.

00:21.022 --> 00:22.688
Okay, we're gonna go in
percutaneously

00:22.690 --> 00:24.223
Through the femoral artery,

00:24.225 --> 00:27.493
Up through the chest,
insert and deploy the valve.

00:27.495 --> 00:29.561
And voilà, wilbur has
a new lease on life.

00:29.563 --> 00:31.563
You've exposed
the femoral artery?

00:31.565 --> 00:35.034
Lin, what's next?
Cannulate the left and right
femoral artery with sheaths.

00:35.036 --> 00:39.138
How do you deal with
a left suicide ventricle? Reid?

00:39.140 --> 00:41.206
Suicide ventricle.
Um...

00:41.208 --> 00:43.575
It is a very rare
condition that--
you're stalling.

00:43.577 --> 00:45.110
Reycraft?

00:45.112 --> 00:47.146
Bolus saline
and beta blockers.

00:47.148 --> 00:49.615
Excellent. In 2010,
"the new England journal"

00:49.617 --> 00:51.450
Published a multicenter trial

00:51.452 --> 00:53.218
On tavi recipients.

00:53.220 --> 00:57.423
How many patients were
in that study, reid?

00:57.425 --> 00:59.158
I'm sorry, dr. Bell.

00:59.160 --> 01:01.527
Gonna have to get back
to you.

01:01.529 --> 01:03.729
The answer is 358.

01:03.731 --> 01:05.631
Ladies and gentlemen,

01:05.633 --> 01:07.499
The patients of hope zion
are in good hands

01:07.501 --> 01:10.369
Because although dr. Reid
doesn't know the answer,

01:10.371 --> 01:12.271
She will get back to us.

01:12.273 --> 01:13.705
(laughs)

01:13.707 --> 01:17.176
Okay, what do you say we save
these pigs' lives, huh?

01:21.481 --> 01:24.083
The contraindication
of performing this procedure?

01:24.085 --> 01:25.751
An a.C.L.-Deficient knee.

01:25.753 --> 01:28.253
Very good.
Dr. Blake, what else?

01:28.255 --> 01:31.356
Dr. Blake, you're going to be
in private practice

01:31.358 --> 01:33.492
In less than a year,
god help us. What else?

01:33.494 --> 01:35.727
A varus or valgus
deficiency?
<i>(man) ¶ there is somebody</i>

01:35.729 --> 01:39.665
Correct. A significant coronal
deformity would call for a--
<i>¶ I long to see</i>

01:39.667 --> 01:41.333
<i>¶ I hope that she</i>
<i>(clears throat)</i>

01:41.335 --> 01:43.635
<i>¶ turns out to be</i>

01:43.637 --> 01:47.439
Dr. Murphy, could you ask your
patient to keep it down, please?
<i>¶ someone who'll watch</i>

01:47.441 --> 01:48.740
<i>¶ over me</i>

01:48.742 --> 01:50.776
Uh, a significant coronal
deformity would call for

01:50.778 --> 01:52.511
A full or... (sighs)
<i>¶ I'm a little lamb</i>

01:52.513 --> 01:54.313
<i>¶ who's lost in the woods</i>

01:54.315 --> 01:56.415
<i>¶ I know I could</i>
<i>dr. Murphy,</i>

01:56.417 --> 01:59.184
Could you ask your patient
to please keep it d--
